WEBVTT

1
00:00:01.140 --> 00:00:04.300
The importance of quantum computing is both understated

2
00:00:04.300 --> 00:00:07.340
and wildly over-hyped at the same time.

3
00:00:07.340 --> 00:00:09.940
Although it won't replace conventional computers

4
00:00:09.940 --> 00:00:14.200
quantum innovation represents a new computing paradigm.

5
00:00:14.200 --> 00:00:17.080
Quantum computers can work in unison with current computing

6
00:00:17.080 --> 00:00:20.979
infrastructure to solve complex problems that were previously

7
00:00:20.980 --> 00:00:23.740
thought impractical or impossible.

8
00:00:23.740 --> 00:00:25.640
This can be paradigm-shifting.

9
00:00:25.640 --> 00:00:28.940
For example the difficulty of factoring large numbers

10
00:00:28.940 --> 00:00:31.640
into their primes is the basis of modern

11
00:00:31.640 --> 00:00:35.420
cryptography. For the size of numbers used in modern public

12
00:00:35.420 --> 00:00:39.480
private key encryption this calculation would take

13
00:00:39.480 --> 00:00:43.580
the fastest conventional computer over 300 trillion years.

14
00:00:43.580 --> 00:00:46.380
For a large-scale quantum computer working

15
00:00:46.380 --> 00:00:50.740
with Shor's algorithm this calculation could take seconds.

16
00:00:50.740 --> 00:00:53.620
Complex problems like this exist across all industries.

17
00:00:53.620 --> 00:00:56.200
The potential applications for quantum computing

18
00:00:56.200 --> 00:00:57.240
are vast.

19
00:00:57.240 --> 00:00:59.560
Quantum computers are already growing larger

20
00:00:59.560 --> 00:01:00.740
and more capable,

21
00:01:00.740 --> 00:01:04.359
as we aim to tackle more complicated problems.

22
00:01:04.360 --> 00:01:08.260
Since 2016, IBM has made quantum computers accessible

23
00:01:08.260 --> 00:01:11.680
to the public via a website with a graphical interface that

24
00:01:11.680 --> 00:01:13.780
looks like a musical score.

25
00:01:13.780 --> 00:01:16.420
and the software development kit Qiskit

26
00:01:16.420 --> 00:01:19.340
which allows users to program quantum computers.

27
00:01:19.340 --> 00:01:22.300
Scientists inside an outside the corporate world

28
00:01:22.300 --> 00:01:23.720
are running experiments

29
00:01:23.720 --> 00:01:27.679
via similar portals. They're exploring approaches to chemistry

30
00:01:27.680 --> 00:01:30.700
and machine learning problems trying to figure out

31
00:01:30.700 --> 00:01:33.300
what sorts of questions they can ask

32
00:01:33.300 --> 00:01:35.380
and how they'll frame those questions

33
00:01:35.380 --> 00:01:39.240
once the technology is further along. Now is the

34
00:01:39.240 --> 00:01:41.300
right time for business leaders to prepare

35
00:01:41.300 --> 00:01:44.840
for quantum. The conditions are in place to experiment

36
00:01:44.840 --> 00:01:47.879
and expand this fundamentally new technology.

37
00:01:47.880 --> 00:01:50.040
Organizations that seek to be at the

38
00:01:50.040 --> 00:01:53.340
forefront of this transformational shift will

39
00:01:53.340 --> 00:01:56.880
seize competitive advantage. This training

40
00:01:56.880 --> 00:01:59.099
will prepare you to start your quantum journey!
